    "in terms of occurrent rationalising causes are always in-principle available, relatively little of the actual practice of action explanation and justification takes this form.",
    "Rather, the answer is more typically given by naming some prospective state of affairs ('in order to cause him harm') or in terms of a \"backwards-looking\" motive ('because he killed my brother') or \"motive in general\" ('to get revenge') (pp. 18-21).",
    "Depending on the circumstances in which the question is asked, such answers will require a greater or lesser degree of \"filling in\" (p. 35) whereby further details are provided so that, seen together, the details form the outline of a pattern in which what the agent does is cast as the fulfilment of a goal or motive attributable to her.",
    "14 Of course, one way to attribute the intention would be to ascribe a basic reason constituting belief-desire pair.",
    "But Anscombe insists both that this is not the only way to do this and that it typically is not the way this should be done."
